<pictures>None<//pictures><Date>1578242937621</Date>< review>
I rolled into Rock 'n Roll Car Wash and rocked a deal...kinda.

I offered $50 bucks for a 59.99 wash 'n wax and dude agreed.

Dropped car off, returned an hour later - car looked pretty good...until I returned home and found lots of dirt spots that were quickly waxed over instead of cleaned off.

So, I took my bottle of wax and a rag, spent 10 minutes with minimal effort and BOOM, car looked great!

I had thought about getting the full detail, glad I didn't because I don't think the rockers at R & R Car Wash would have delivered the goods.

Not bad, not great - 3.5 stars.

Might try again, might not?< /review>

< review>
Picked up my car and drove home.  It was then I noticed that the plastic grille had not been treated.  Also, plastic trim on the lift gate was not detailed properly.  Immediately returned to the car wash.  Being irate, I pointed out the deficiencies.  They told me the grille was weathered and couldn't be restored.  Meguires makes black plastic restore liquid.  They put some of their liquid on it which didn't help.  They then used something abrasive on the rear plastic piece which scratched it and told me other blemishes couldn't be corrected.  Back at home I used cleaner wax to restore the rear plastic trim.  Tomorrow I'll buy some Meguiars black plastic restore liquid for the grille.   Then I noticed that paint had been ground off the passenger side door handles.  Also, many imperfections were missed on the roof.  Never again.<//review>

113803940814573041855< /UserId.>
< text>
Black cars are hard to clean. I'll go with that, since my car came out with a few water splotch spots, but you can't expect a detail job from a drive in drive out wash. You just come with mid to low level expectations and expect everything to turn out A-OK. And A-OK it was, hell my car needed this for the nice sunny day.

Here's the format for the former self-washers, like myself. You drive up to the yellow line, leave the keys in the car, someone asks you what kinda wash you want and maybe up-sells a bit. Take the receipt to the cashier then you wait on your car with the other folks. I usually like to tip the persons drying my car at that time, but here they have a big sealed tip box with a sign that said they shared tips. I even saw the owner come out to help dry my car. I like that sort of humbling thing.

-=-11 bucks-=- For a vacuum and wash, now that's a deal. From where I'm from, I would pay almost twice that. I dig it. If I lived around here, I probably would have been a repeat customer. Is this really the "Only hand wash in South Bay"?. If it was, I was lucky to have stumbled upon it with my dirty car needs.< /text>

< Review>
We arrived an hour before closing and the guy said as long as we can eat with in the hour then we can sit down to eat. Nice little spot but don't go an hour before closing. Our food was not warm but luke warm. Not sure if it was only heated slightly so we could eat faster but the sauce for the chicken enchiladas was just to much of a sweet mole sauce. Not my preference. I like my mole sauce more savory but keep in mind I was eating chicken enchiladas so the mole sauce just did not taste great. They did give alot of sour cream and fake guacamole. Beans were dried and the rice was the only thing I liked on the plate. My husband had to force him self to eat his wet burrito because he was hungry but would not go back either. Because it was the end of the night our food was packed in to go clamshells. We were hoping for hot food but no success. I do not recommend this place.< /Review>

<rate>4</rate><Review>Went here for lunch the other day. I knew this place when the Asian guy owned it (a few years ago?). They always made quality and quantity, reasonably priced. The salsa bar was the best in the area. No more salsa bar/Covid.

Well, the prices increased (about 30%). Quality was still OK and portions are smaller. A regular burrito is now $10. I asked for shredded chicken, refried beans (not whole beans) and no rice. The burrito was 70% refried beans and 30% chicken (a few chunks). It was tasty but it was mostly refried beans. They also put some pico de gallo on the inside as well.

Service was good (got the burrito in about 7 minutes - it wasn't busy/I went in just after 1015am). Basically, paying much more, for smaller portions and less meat.

Fortunately, there are many other places in the area that give quality and quantity for about the same price (Los Perricos to name one).</Review><pictures>None< /pictures><Resp>None</Resp>< Gmap_id>

Go somewhere else. There are plenty of other Mexican options in the Dublin area. Ordered tamales and pozole for a to-go order on a quiet Tuesday evening. For those unfamiliar, these should be "easy to serve" foods from a restaurant standpoint. Not here at Taqueria Azteca. It took more than 45 minutes for the order to be ready. <Gmap_id>0x808fec6bf246e1d5:0xb462d9ba0b360c30</Gmap_id>< Review>
The ladies working were super nice. Now the bad part, I ordered 2 beef enchiladas with rice and beans (combination). The enchiladas are a complete joke, it is a tortilla with a teaspoon of ground meat rolled and covered in sauce. My pinky finger is bigger. Now imagine two of these on a huge plate of beans and rice. I didn't order rice and beans with a side of two tiny pencil sized enchiladas! Twelve dollars for dinner? and I could of ate myself sick at taco bell for nine dollars?.  Another issue was on their guacamole, avocados are expensive and delicious, you mash and LIGHTLY season them for the flavor to come out. They destroy perfectly good avocados with massive amounts of lime juice. YUCK! Why not just add lime juice to mayonnaise, if all you want is lime flavored goo.

So at the end of the day, there biggest problem for me is value. I felt like my 12 bucks got me a big plate of beans and red sauce. Too bad, they could have a great business if they just made good food at a good value.<//Review>

<name>Thomas Wilson< /name></record></dataset><record>
<review>Don't you hate those garages, or dealers, who are just part replacers or want to sell you so much more than your car really needs?  Their estimates always look like more when it comes time to paying.  THIS DOES NOT HAPPEN at McWilliams & Walden.  Have been going here since 2008.  Honest, awesome customer service, quality work, no BS.  Alignments, tires, brakes, oil changes, and STAR certified smog testing.

March 2021,
The last week of February 2021 I brought my car in for an oil change and tire rotation.  The assigned mechanic completed those tasks and upon inspection noticed that one strut assembly was leaking, and a motor mount was cracked and near failing.  I returned a week or so later and had the struts and motor mounts replaced.  The mechanic then noticed a coolant leak.  The leak was traced to the lower portion of the timing chain cover.  The garage replaced the cover seal.  Close inspection after the disassembly showed the seal had pinched during assembly at the factory causing a bad seal and galvanic corrosion between the iron block and aluminum cover.  This was a very serious problem.  Had it not been found it could have become larger and completely failed.  The engine would have lost all coolant, seriously overheated, and basically burned up.  This could have happened at any time or place.  I cannot thank McWilliams and Walden's entire cadre enough for outstanding dedication to caring for customers and their cars.<//review><date>1615503056270<//date>< UserId.>

Purchased my 2005 Mitsubishi Outlander here and I couldn't be happier. I emailed the dealership inquiring about the vehicle; I was surprised I got a respond back quick. They suggested I send my credit info through their website, which makes the process easier when I go in to finalize the deal. <rating>3</rating>< text>
This place seems like one which relies off of the atmosphere and overall vibe rather than what they actually provide. I had a friendly greeting when I walked in and sat down immediately. The haircut was decent, not the best I've had, but not bad. I got a short 2 minute massage with a hand vibrating tool and that was that. The problem I had was that they simply went through my cut as fast as they could with noone else waiting and it was very expensive without anyone ever telling me the price or me seeing anything posted. I could have gone to Sport Clips and gotten just as good of a cut with a hair wash and full massage shave and everything for less than what just one cut cost me here. I prefer to support a local barber shop though so next time I will save a few bucks and go somewhere else. Just simply not worth $30 for a standard haircut< /text>

<rating>1< /rating>< review>
Went in for a haircut and beard trim/lineup. The "master barber" who has been cutting hair since 1960 did not know how to use a straight razor whatsoever. After a miserable attempt to line up one side of my beard, I had to directly show him what it means to get a line up. After struggling to do one side, he goes to do the other, and when I look in the mirror, the two sides are so uneven it's painful. He wouldn't have even noticed it or said anything if I didn't bluntly point out this horrible job. This experience is especially disappointing because I came in as a first time customer, told them I had a photo shoot the next day so the details had to be right, paid a whopping $43 for a lousy haircut (I normally pay $30 w/tip at senor barbers, and they always get it spot on). On top of that, my barber was not warm and friendly, he made zero effort to make this a good experience for me. After all this, I jumped out of my seat and went to another barbershop to remedy the mistakes they made.

If you want a proper haircutting experience, attention to detail, and a staff that truly cares for their clients and their business, go elsewhere. 0/10 for me.<//review>

< text>
Service is awesome here, and by that I mean honest and genuine, they take responsibility for their work, are fair and give the best deals for what you are trying to get done.

I had vibrations in acceleration on my minivan's steering wheel and drivers side for a while, and after changing a whole new set of tires and also get alignment done, it didn't go away. After asking 4 different places I decided to go with M STAR, since my mother-in-law had taken the van in before, they said they would waive the $100 inspection fee. (It's higher than a small shop in Alhambra but cheaper than toyota dealer for sure). So now it's free, I'm happy, I take it in and they tell me a few hours later that the 2 axles are unbalanced and they'll need to replace. Turns out it's $900/ea original retail price, but they have OEM w labor&tax $320/ea. Ok, this is big drop for me, but I know it's really important as my wife and I share the same vehicle and we both did not like how dangerous the car felt w the vibrations. So I went ahead to confirm it,

When I arrived to pick up the car, get this:
They said before they changed these axles out for my mother in law so this is the part's fault and it's on them,
- they are waiving the labor fees,
- crediting me the full amount I paid last time (showed me the receipt from last time),
- sending the fairy new axles in for warranty replacements (showed me pictures they took of the parts and the work)
- and all I have to pay for is the difference between the new and better quality axles they put in today and the alignment. Ends up being $230! I'm very happy they were so honest and responsible and good business practice.

This place is legit. The people are good. I have written my fair share of reviews on shady and evil auto shops who swindle you or unsuspecting, especially since we didn't know. They could've kept the work from last time from me, I wouldn't have known. But they chose to be honest and genuine, and you CANT ask any more from an auto shop!!

Highly recommend!!< /text>

<review>This is the only poke place I go to in Pleasanton. I have tried others, and each time I've wished that I had just gone to this place. Prime Poke has a good option of fish to choose from, and the sauces are really good. I always order the two protein, because the three is too much for me, and I have always gotten the tuna for the free scoop, the marinated salmon, and the marinated tuna (I dont remember the exact name). For the last meat you order, they let you choose mix ins, I get the cucumber, cilantro, and serrano. Then for sauces my favorite for the mix ins in spicy poke and teriyaki. For the sauces on top, I would recommend sriracha and the spicy mayo, if you like spice, or just the spicy mayo if you want it to be mild. However, even with all that spicy stuff on top, it is not an overpowering amount of spice. I tried for the first a topping, I forget the name but I'll include a picture, and it was a good amount of crisp but the pieces were just a little too large for my taste. If you're in Pleasanton, and feel like poke, I would definitely try this place out!</review><Pics>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOUWrYO_PxoZQLuX1RvS7IhwiCpqqzjb-B7IpeY=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]</Pics><Response>None</Response>< gmapID>

<review>Went in despite my previous experiences. Just got brand new tires with alignment and balancing done February 5th. They told me everything was fine. today they check the alignment did an inspection under the tires and rotated the tires, again they told me everything is fine everything is good. what you are seeing in the picture is oil-contaminated grease on the right rear shock which is unknown mileage. This indicates that the rear shocks are leaking in should be recommended for a replacement. in the past they have also said everything was fine during their inspection, when the vehicle was taking in with burnt-out bulbs cracked and splitting wiper blades and other major issues. They failed to do with the paperwork properly, as well as filling to provide inspection reports which their own paperwork says you're supposed to get. and the saddest part is every time I've taken my vehicles in I have worked with the assistant service manager. I've complained to him multiple times about the poor quality of their technicians work, even letting him know that I am trained and have worked as a technician myself so I know what a good job is supposed to look like. <Rating>5<//Rating>< review>
I went into Mossy Nissan of El Cajon for a routine oil change. When I went in I decided to browse around the showroom for a SUV for my family. I was approached by a young gentleman by the name of Anthony who asked if I had any questions. I told him that I was interested in trading in my vehicle to get an SUV for my family. He asked me if I had time so he could show me around and give me some options that may suit me. I told him yeah and he was very hospitable as well by offering me something to drink. We went out to the car lot and he showed me a list of different options in my price range. he was not pushy or trying to shove a certain vehicle at me. Instead we started with the base models and worked our way up. He let me test drive two different models and I fell in love with each one. We then came back to the dealership and worked on seeing what the price range would be for my monthly bill. Unfortunately I wasn't able to get the financing that I wanted so I passed on that deal. But he did not let me leave unhappy because he presented me another option that I ended up taking. He asked me if I was interested in trading my older car in for a newer car because they had dealership bonuses and rebates for purchasing a newer vehicle. I did want a new car no matter what and something more spacious and luxurious. He showed me the Nissan Altima 2018 Sr series. Very sporty and rims and at the same price as the base model at the time of the sale. Got me a great deal on the trade-in value of my vehicle and we sign the paperwork. Anthony took his customer service to the next level by meeting me at my job because I was in a hurry to get to work. We filled out the paperwork at my job and made it official. This guy is top-class customer service and the dealership is very lucky to have him. I give the dealership and Anthony a 5-star rating because it is well deserved.< /review>

<Review>This review is specifically for the service center: Robb and Elijah.
Went to my mechanic yesterday because my check engine light was on and showing a P0101 error meaning there is an issue with the Mass Airflow Sensor. Mechanic called Nissan to see if he could order the part, Joe in the parts department notified him it was under warranty and advised me to make an appointment ASAP. My mechanic cleared the error codes to turn off my check engine light and sent me on my way.
Showed up at 7am for my appointment this morning and left my car with Robb. Got a call around 9am that because the error code was cleared, Nissan could not service my car. At no point yesterday did anyone advise those codes needed to be kept in the system for it to be covered under warranty. Spoke with Service Manager Elijah who advised that there was nothing he could do until my Check Engine Light came on again. For them to hook up the computer to my car takes no more than 5 minutes (I watched my mechanic do it yesterday) there was NO reason it should have taken over 2 hours. All over a $20 part, he was citing company policy and attempting to blame the miscommunication on my mechanic and not taking responsibility for the actions of him team. I got nothing more than an apology for the frustration experience. As they say, never ruin an apology with an excuse.
So now I'm expected to drive my car, which has been having performance issues due to the MAF, unsafely with a KNOWN issue from here to Arizona this weekend. This is by far the worst customer service experience I have ever dealt with.<//Review></record></dataset><record>

Yes, it is true that a vehicle can be sold as new with high mileage and may have it for a number of reasons. However, regardless of the mileage on your vehicle, your new car warranties (3 year - 36,000 miles and 5 year 60,000 miles) won't begin until you purchase the vehicle so you will have the full extent of the warranty until roughly 36,500/ 60,500 (to the exact mileage that you purchased it at). < review>
I tagged along with a friend to go car shopping, and we ended up at Mossy El Cajon after only going to one other place. As soon as we walked on the lot, Manny walked right up to us and introduced himself. We explained that we were really just looking, and he stuck around to answer our questions anyway. My friend didnt have the best credit, and Manny explained to him the process, and that he was sure they would be able to finance him. It turns out that not only were they able to finance him, but they got him an amazing rate with a payment that fit his budget. They did not pressure him at all, but simply ran the numbers to show him what they could do for him. I have bought cars in the past, but this is by far the best dealership I have ever been to. My friend ended up buying a 2012 Nissan that day, and drove off in it within a couple of hours. While shopping with my friend, I became interested in a 2013 Altima. I ended up back at the lot 2 days later, and I also drove off the lot within a couple of hours. Manny helped us both out, and has gone out of his way to call us both to check up on us. They also have a kid friendly environment where they put a movie on for my 2 kids while we did all the paperwork to keep them from getting bored.This was by far the best car buying experience I have ever had. If you are looking for a new car, I would definitly recommend Manny, and the rest of the team at Mossy Nissan of El Cajon!<//review>

< review>
My husband and I wanted to purchase a truck, we came here because of their reputation and the fact that I had to turn in my Nissan Leaf (2014) early because I had hit the mileage too soon and did not want to finish the lease.  So we brought in our Leased Leaf and our minivan as trade-ins for the Nissan truck we bought with David Gunn.  Through the negotiations I wanted to be able to turn in my Nissan Lease with no penalties as a good customer for purchasing a brand new 2017 truck.  This appeared to be part of the deal and we left both vehicles and drove away with our new Truck.  In June I received a phone call from the Nissan Leasing agency saying I owed them for several lease payments and they would go to collections within the week if they were not paid (the lease was up in May according to their paperwork but I left it with the dealership in March....)
I called the dealership and  spoke to Travis (Finance Manager)  and after some searching it turned out my Nissan Leaf was never "grounded" and none of the paperwork was completed so basically it was as if the car was still mine. Travis told me he would get Manny Jurado (our finance guy from the purchase) and David Gunn in the loop and ensure this was cleared up ASAP.  Nothing happened.  I have had to call them over and over only to receive promises of things being resolved when in reality all the phone calls and communication between the two companies has fallen on me.  When I finally got a hold of David Gunn after a promised phone call from Manny Jurado never came through David clearly had NO knowledge of anything that was going on. (this was over several weeks!)

To make matters worse they turned in the Leaf in June without giving me a call to see if I had the charger cable for the car which resulted in the Nissan leasing group sending me a bill for a missing Tool (no description and another phone call) for $896!!! Now after trying to drop off the cable which we had but did not know had not been turned in (major lack of communication) they turned us down and said we have to mail it back to Texas to get our record cleared.
I clearly remember the Manager that night we purchased the truck asking us if they will get a 5 star review....at the time we said yes but I am sure glad I waited....this team needs to get its act together and take care of their customers.  I am extremely disappointed with this bungled process and their lack of concern.  It's clear they only care about selling the cars and not about any issues they create for the customer after walking out that door.<//review>
